Right after we took this picture, homophobic slurs were hurled at us from across the street. The worst part is, the same thing happened the day before. It’s not often that this happens to us. But for it to happen twice in a weekend was jarring. I was hurt by the comments but more so concerned about the queer folks whose survival depends on hiding their existence. I used to do the same.

Luckily, I’m able to live in a place where I can express my queerness without resistance (or so I thought). But that’s just not the case for most queer folks in the world. I was quickly reminded that the work is never done. Our community is still very much under attack and we can’t let our guard down for a second. 

I will continue to kiss my partner in public. I will continue to hold his hand. I will continue to love freely and express myself as GOD intended. I write this message with a heap of sadness in my heart. But also, an abundance of hope in my soul.

Went to @thebroadmuseum and couldn’t stop staring at this picture. It’s messy. It’s beautiful. It’s life. 

As a young butch queen, I couldn’t wait to grow up so my “messy life” would make sense. I’d soon learn that it never would. But I did learn how to live and breathe in the mess. To flourish in it. To own it. To make it beautiful. 

I’m blessed to live the life I live. As messy as it can be, I wouldn’t trade it for the world. It makes me who I am. And I love that person so very much. 
❤️

West Coast Awards Ball!

💜I haven’t walked a ball in 10+ years but ballroom will always run through my veins. It raised me. It pushed me to grow. It showed me how great community can be. It was there with open arms when other spaces were not. 

💜When I was coming up in the scene, I had a ton of mentors, fathers, mothers, and siblings helping me on my journey. It’s now my mission to do the same for the next generation. 

💜Walking isn’t as important for me (although sometimes I get the urge haha). I had my time and I loved every bit of it. Now, it’s about the children.

Butchqueen Diary… 

Don’t confuse “being real” with being an “asshole”. I used to confuse the two a lot. Admittedly, I still do 🙃. 

But I’m learning that there are many ways to tell your truth with kindness, empathy, and compassion.

Words can’t express the gratitude I feel after going to @glaad’s Black Queer Creative Summit! 

I met the best people and had an experience like no other. I didn’t get enough pics but here are some of my favorites. 

Love y’all for life!

Butch Queen Advice… It’s World AIDS Day! 

This year’s theme, “World AIDS Day 35: Remember and Commit,” pays tribute to those we have lost to HIV/AIDS. 

The impact of this epidemic has been profound, affecting individuals, families, and entire communities across the globe. 

Remembering the lives lost not only honors their memory but also emphasizes the urgency of our commitment to end the HIV epidemic.

*Correction- The House of Extravaganza was founded by Hector Valle. Not the Hector that I speak of in the video. There was more than one Hector! Both of them great butch queens. ❤️
